Explanation and reasoning:

- I inspected controllers/invoices.js and routes/invoices.js to determine which handler processes POST /invoices. The routes file maps POST '/' to createInvoice, and createInvoice in controllers reads req.body and saves a new InvoiceModel instance.
- I inspected models/InvoiceModel.js to derive the expected invoice structure: it defines fields (dueDate, currency, items, rates, vat, total, subTotal, notes, status, invoiceNumber, type, creator, totalAmountReceived, client, paymentRecords, createdAt) and detailed substructures for items, client, and paymentRecords.
- The POST /invoices endpoint therefore expects a request body containing an invoice object. In Swagger 2.0 this is represented as a single "body" Parameter Object whose schema mirrors the Mongoose model fields.
- I did not add any fields that are not present in the model and did not use $ref. I represented date fields as strings with format "date-time" and numeric fields as "number". The model uses some fields as strings (e.g., unitPrice, quantity, discount) so they are typed as strings here as well.
- No field-level "required" constraints were inferred from the code, so the schema properties are optional; the body parameter itself is marked required (the endpoint expects a body).

